{"title_page": "Mikhail Gershenzon", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Mikhail Gershenzon\n| image         = Pasternak gershenzon.jpg\n| image_size    = 180px\n| caption       = <small>Mikhail Gershenzon in 1917, by [[Leonid Pasternak]]</small>\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1869|07|01}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1925|02|19|1869|07|01}}\n| death_place   = [[Moscow]]\n| residence     = [[Russian Empire]]<br>[[Soviet Union]]\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = [[Imperial Moscow University|Imperial Moscow University (1894)]]\n}}\n'''Mikhail Osipovich Gershenzon''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u0301\u043b \u041e\u0301\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0413\u0435\u0440\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0437\u043e\u0301\u043d}}) ([[Kishinev]], {{OldStyleDate|July 13|1869|July 1}} -  [[Moscow]], 19 February 1925) was a [[Russians|Russian]] [[scholar]], [[essayist]] and [[editing|editor]]. He studied history, philosophy, and political science at [[Moscow University]], graduating in 1894. From graduation until the Bolshevik revolution he was unable to obtain an official [[academic]] position because he was [[Jewish]]. He was a literary reviewer for ''Nauchnoe Slovo'' (Scientific word) from 1903 to 1905 and for ''[[Vestnik Evropy]]'' (Herald of Europe) in 1907\u201308, and was literary editor of ''Kriticheskoe Obozrenie'' (Critical review), 1907\u201309. He had a [[common-law]] relationship with Maria Goldenveizer from 1904 ([[Judaism|Judaists]] and [[Orthodox Christians]] were unable to marry legally); they had a daughter and a son. In 1909 he edited the famous essay collection ''[[Vekhi]]'', for which he wrote the introduction and an essay.\n\nDuring the Civil War he worked in various sections of the [[People's Commissariat for Education]] (Narkompros). He was first chair of the Moscow Writers' Union in 1918 and of the All-Russian Writers' Union in 1920\u201321, during which years he was also a member of the leadership of Narkompros; he was head of the literary section, Moscow Academy of Artistic Sciences from 1922 to 1925.\n\n==Selected publications==\n* \u201cThe Destinies of the Jewish People\u201d. [http://www.telospress.com ''Telos''] 58 (Winter 1983-84). New York: Telos Press.\n\n==References==\n* Berman, Iakov, ''Gershenzon, Bibliografiia'', [[Odessa]], Odespoligraf, 1928.\n* Brian Horowitz, ''The Myth of A.S. Pushkin in Russia's Silver Age: M. O. Gershenzon-Pushinist''.  Northwestern University Press, 1997. (Republished in Russian translation: ''Mikhail Gershenzon Pushkinist: Pushkinskii mif v serebrianom veke russkoi literatury'', Moscow: Minuvshee, 2004.)\n* \u201cM. O. Gershenzon, Alexander Pushkin, the Bible and the Flaws of Jewish Nationalism,\u201d ''Znanie. Ponimanie. Umenie'' [''Knowledge. Understanding. Skill''], 4, 2016.\n* \u201cM. O. Gershenzon and George Florovsky ('Metaphysical Philosophers of Russian History'),\u201d ''Canadian-American Slavonic Studies'', 34, no. 3, 2001, 365\u2013374.\n* \u201cUnity and Disunity in Landmarks: The Rivalry between Petr Struve and Mikhail Gershenzon,\u201d ''Studies in East European Thought'', 51, no. 1, March 1999, 61\u201378.\n* \u201cFrom the Annals of the Literary Life of Russia's Silver Age: The Tempestuous Relationship of S. A. Vengerov and M. O. Gershenzon,\u201d ''Wiener Slawistischer Almanach'' 35, 1995, 77\u201395; abridged form in \u201c''Oh Rus!\u201d Festschrift to Honor Professor Hugh McLean'', eds. S. Karlinsky, J. Rice and B. Scheer, Berkeley: Berkeley Slavic Specialties, 1995, 406-419.\n* \u201cThe End of a Friendship: the Russian-Jewish Rift in Twentieth-Century Russian Philosophy: N. A. Berdiaev and M. O. Gershenzon,\u201d ''Russian Review'' 53: 4, October 1994, 497-514. Republished: ''Twentieth-Century Literary Criticism'', ed. Scot Peacock, New York: Gale 67, 1997, 75-83. \u201cOt Vekh' k russkoi revoliutsii: dva filosofa N. A. Berdiaev i M. O. Gershenzon.\u201d''Vestnik russkogo studencheskogo khristianskogo dvizheniia'' 166, May, 1992, 89-132.\n* \u201cM. O. Gershenzon and the Perception of a Leader in Russia's Silver-Age Culture,\u201d ''Wiener Slawistischer Almanach''  29, 1992, 45-73.\n* \u201cBefore the Fall\u201d (On ''Vekhi'' [''Landmarks'']), ''The American Scholar,'' Spring, 1992, 290-296.\n* Memoirs of Gershenzon\u2019s daughter. \u201cLes premiers pas dans la vie: les ann\u00e9es de mon immortalit\u00e9,\u201d ''La revue des \u00e9tudes slaves'' 63, 1991, 621\u2013629.\n* {{citation\n |last=Horowitz \n |first=Brian \n |year=2016 \n |title=Unity in \"Landmarks\" (\"Vekhi\")?: The Tensions between Petr Struve and Mikhail Gershenzon \n |journal=Znanie. Ponimanie. Umenie \n |volume=13 \n |url=http://journals.mosgu.ru/zpu/article/view/278/321 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ibXpjIdV?url=http://journals.mosgu.ru/zpu/article/download/278/321 \n |archivedate=28 June 2016 \n |accessdate=28 June 2016 \n |issue=2 \n |pages=329\u2013342 \n |DOI=10.17805/zpu.2016.2.29 \n |url-status=dead \n}}\n* {{cite book| author =  | chapter = | chapter-url = | format = | url =  | title =Imperial Moscow University: 1755-1917: encyclopedic dictionary | orig-year = | agency = A. Andreev, D. Tsygankov | edition = |location= Moscow |year= 2010 |publisher= Russian political encyclopedia (ROSSPEN) |at=  |volume=  |issue = | pages =156\u2013157 | page =  | series =  | isbn = 978-5-8243-1429-8| ref =Imperial Moscow University}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gershenzon, Mikhail}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1925 deaths]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Russian political scientists]]\n[[Category:Jewish Russian writers]]\n[[Category:Imperial Moscow University alumni]]\n\n\n{{Russia-academic-bio-stub}}\n{{polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Mikhail Gershenzon\n| image         = Pasternak gershenzon.jpg\n| image_size    = 180px\n| caption       = <small>Mikhail Gershenzon in 1917, by [[Leonid Pasternak]]</small>\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1869|07|01}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1925|02|19|1869|07|01}}\n| death_place   = [[Moscow]]\n| residence     = [[Russian Empire]]<br>[[Soviet Union]]\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = [[Imperial Moscow University|Imperial Moscow University (1894)]]\n}}\n'''Mikhail Osipovich Gershenzon''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u0301\u043b \u041e\u0301\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0413\u0435\u0440\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0437\u043e\u0301\u043d}}) ([[Kishinev]], {{OldStyleDate|July 13|1869|July 1}} -  [[Moscow]], 19 February 1925) was a [[Russians|Russian]] [[scholar]], [[essayist]] and [[editing|editor]]. He studied history, philosophy, and political science at [[Moscow University]], graduating in 1894. From graduation until the Bolshevik revolution he was unable to obtain an official [[academic]] position because he was [[Jewish]]. He was a literary reviewer for ''Nauchnoe Slovo'' (Scientific word) from 1903 to 1905 and for ''[[Vestnik Evropy]]'' (Herald of Europe) in 1907-08, and was literary editor of ''Kriticheskoe Obozrenie'' (Critical review), 1907-09. He had a [[common-law]] relationship with Maria Goldenveizer from 1904 ([[Judaism|Judaists]] and [[Orthodox Christians]] were unable to marry legally); they had a daughter and a son. In 1909 he edited the famous essay collection ''[[Vekhi]]'', for which he wrote the introduction and an essay.\n\nDuring the Civil War he worked in various sections of the [[People's Commissariat for Education]] (Narkompros). He was first chair of the Moscow Writers' Union in 1918 and of the All-Russian Writers' Union in 1920-21, during which years he was also a member of the leadership of Narkompros; he was head of the literary section, Moscow Academy of Artistic Sciences from 1922 to 1925.\n\n==Selected publications==\n* \u201cThe Destinies of the Jewish People\u201d. [http://www.telospress.com ''Telos''] 58 (Winter 1983-84). New York: Telos Press.\n\n==References==\n* Berman, Iakov, ''Gershenzon, Bibliografiia'', [[Odessa]], Odespoligraf, 1928.\n* Brian Horowitz, ''The Myth of A.S. Pushkin in Russia's Silver Age: M. O. Gershenzon-Pushinist''.  Northwestern University Press, 1997. (Republished in Russian translation: ''Mikhail Gershenzon Pushkinist: Pushkinskii mif v serebrianom veke russkoi literatury'', Moscow: Minuvshee, 2004.)\n* \u201cM. O. Gershenzon, Alexander Pushkin, the Bible and the Flaws of Jewish Nationalism,\u201d ''Znanie. Ponimanie. Umenie'' [''Knowledge. Understanding. Skill''], 4, 2016.\n* \u201cM. O. Gershenzon and George Florovsky ('Metaphysical Philosophers of Russian History'),\u201d ''Canadian-American Slavonic Studies'', 34, no. 3, 2001, 365-374.\n* \u201cUnity and Disunity in Landmarks: The Rivalry between Petr Struve and Mikhail Gershenzon,\u201d ''Studies in East European Thought'', 51, no. 1, March 1999, 61-78.\n* \u201cFrom the Annals of the Literary Life of Russia's Silver Age: The Tempestuous Relationship of S. A. Vengerov and M. O. Gershenzon,\u201d ''Wiener Slawistischer Almanach'' 35, 1995, 77-95; abridged form in \u201c''Oh Rus!\u201d Festschrift to Honor Professor Hugh McLean'', eds. S. Karlinsky, J. Rice and B. Scheer, Berkeley: Berkeley Slavic Specialties, 1995, 406-419.\n* \u201cThe End of a Friendship: the Russian-Jewish Rift in Twentieth-Century Russian Philosophy: N. A. Berdiaev and M. O. Gershenzon,\u201d ''Russian Review'' 53: 4, October 1994, 497-514. Republished: ''Twentieth-Century Literary Criticism'', ed. Scot Peacock, New York: Gale 67, 1997, 75-83. \u201cOt Vekh' k russkoi revoliutsii: dva filosofa N. A. Berdiaev i M. O. Gershenzon.\u201d''Vestnik russkogo studencheskogo khristianskogo dvizheniia'' 166, May, 1992, 89-132.\n* \u201cM. O. Gershenzon and the Perception of a Leader in Russia's Silver-Age Culture,\u201d ''Wiener Slawistischer Almanach''  29, 1992, 45-73.\n* \u201cBefore the Fall\u201d (On ''Vekhi'' [''Landmarks'']), ''The American Scholar,'' Spring, 1992, 290-296.\n* Memoirs of Gershenzon\u2019s daughter. \u201cLes premiers pas dans la vie: les ann\u00e9es de mon immortalit\u00e9,\u201d ''La revue des \u00e9tudes slaves'' 63, 1991, 621-629.\n* {{citation\n |last=Horowitz \n |first=Brian \n |year=2016 \n |title=Unity in \"Landmarks\" (\"Vekhi\")?: The Tensions between Petr Struve and Mikhail Gershenzon \n |journal=Znanie. Ponimanie. Umenie \n |volume=13 \n |url=http://journals.mosgu.ru/zpu/article/view/278/321 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ibXpjIdV?url=http://journals.mosgu.ru/zpu/article/download/278/321 \n |archivedate=28 June 2016 \n |accessdate=28 June 2016 \n |issue=2 \n |pages=329\u2013342 \n |DOI=10.17805/zpu.2016.2.29 \n |url-status=dead \n}}\n* {{cite book| author =  | chapter = | chapter-url = | format = | url =  | title =Imperial Moscow University: 1755-1917: encyclopedic dictionary | orig-year = | agency = A. Andreev, D. Tsygankov | edition = |location= Moscow |year= 2010 |publisher= Russian political encyclopedia (ROSSPEN) |at=  |volume=  |issue = | pages =156\u2013157 | page =  | series =  | isbn = 978-5-8243-1429-8| ref =Imperial Moscow University}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gershenzon, Mikhail}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1925 deaths]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Russian political scientists]]\n[[Category:Jewish Russian writers]]\n[[Category:Imperial Moscow University alumni]]\n\n\n{{Russia-academic-bio-stub}}\n{{polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1907-08 \u2192 1907\u201308 (7)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mikhail_Gershenzon"}
{"title_page": "Andr\u00e9 du Pisani", "text_new": "{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Andr\u00e9 du Pisani\n| image              = Andre du pisani.jpg\n| caption            = du Pisani in 2015\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = 15 January 1949\n| birth_place        = [[Windhoek]], [[South West Africa]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Namibian\n| occupation         = Political scientist, author, professor\n| spouse             = \n| alma_mater         = [[Stellenbosch University]]<br>[[London School of Economics]]<br>[[University of Cape Town]]<br>[[University of Cambridge]]\n| influences         = \n| workplaces         = [[University of Namibia]]\n| main_interests     = [[Political science]]\n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = \n| signature          = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Andr\u00e9 du Pisani''' (born 15 January 1949) is a [[Namibia|Namibian]] political scientist, author of several books, articles and journals, he has written several conference papers for SADC, the Namibian government and several ministries, he is a Professor at the [[University of Namibia Department of Political Science]]. Du Pisani has been a professor at the university since 1998.\n\n==Education==\nThe Windhoek native earned his bachelor's degree from [[Stellenbosch University]] in [[South Africa]] in 1971 and an honours in politics from Stellenbosch in 1972. He later earned a master's degree in politics from Stellenbosch in 1975. From 1975 to 1976, du Pisani was a research student at the [[London School of Economics]]. In 1988, he earned his Ph.D. in politics from the [[University of Cape Town]]. From 1995\u201396, he did post-doctoral research through the Global Security Fellows Initiative at the [[University of Cambridge]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>[http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=35 Andr\u00e9 du Pisani] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611171550/http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=35 |date=June 11, 2011 }} at the Namibia Institute for Democracy, Windhoek, 2007</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|title=Namibia, the Politics of Continuity and Change|publisher=Jonathan Ball Publishing|isbn=0-86850-092-5}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:du Pisani, Andre}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:White Namibian people]]\n[[Category:Namibian political scientists]]\n[[Category:Namibian people of South African descent]]\n[[Category:People from Windhoek]]\n[[Category:Stellenbosch University alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:University of Cape Town alumni]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:University of Namibia academics]]\n\n\n{{Namibia-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-academic-bio-stub}}\n{{polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Andr\u00e9 du Pisani\n| image              = Andre du pisani.jpg\n| caption            = du Pisani in 2015\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = 15 January 1949\n| birth_place        = [[Windhoek]], [[South West Africa]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Namibian\n| occupation         = Political scientist, author, professor\n| spouse             = \n| alma_mater         = [[Stellenbosch University]]<br>[[London School of Economics]]<br>[[University of Cape Town]]<br>[[University of Cambridge]]\n| influences         = \n| workplaces         = [[University of Namibia]]\n| main_interests     = [[Political science]]\n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = \n| signature          = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Andr\u00e9 du Pisani''' (born 15 January 1949) is a [[Namibia|Namibian]] political scientist, author of several books, articles and journals, he has written several conference papers for SADC, the Namibian government and several ministries, he is a Professor at the [[University of Namibia Department of Political Science]]. Du Pisani has been a professor at the university since 1998.\n\n==Education==\nThe Windhoek native earned his bachelor's degree from [[Stellenbosch University]] in [[South Africa]] in 1971 and an honours in politics from Stellenbosch in 1972. He later earned a master's degree in politics from Stellenbosch in 1975. From 1975 to 1976, du Pisani was a research student at the [[London School of Economics]]. In 1988, he earned his Ph.D. in politics from the [[University of Cape Town]]. From 1995-96, he did post-doctoral research through the Global Security Fellows Initiative at the [[University of Cambridge]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>[http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=35 Andr\u00e9 du Pisani] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611171550/http://www.nid.org.na/view_book_entry.php?book_id=35 |date=June 11, 2011 }} at the Namibia Institute for Democracy, Windhoek, 2007</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|title=Namibia, the Politics of Continuity and Change|publisher=Jonathan Ball Publishing|isbn=0-86850-092-5}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:du Pisani, Andre}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:White Namibian people]]\n[[Category:Namibian political scientists]]\n[[Category:Namibian people of South African descent]]\n[[Category:People from Windhoek]]\n[[Category:Stellenbosch University alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:University of Cape Town alumni]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:University of Namibia academics]]\n\n\n{{Namibia-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-academic-bio-stub}}\n{{polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1995-96 \u2192 1995\u201396", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andr%C3%A9_du_Pisani"}
{"title_page": "Alan Dowty", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| image         = Alan Dowty Shimer College Chicago 2008.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Alan Dowty in 2008.\n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1940|01|15}}\n| occupation    = Professor emeritus\n| education     = BA, MA, Ph.D.\n| alma_mater    = [[Shimer College]]; [[University of Chicago]]\n| genre         = nonfiction\n| subject       = international relations\n}}\n\n'''Alan Dowty''' (born January 15, 1940) is an American author, historian and Professor of International Relations and Political Science Emeritus, [[University of Notre Dame]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Alan Dowty|url=http://politicalscience.nd.edu/faculty/faculty-list/alan-dowty/|publisher=nd.edu|accessdate=30 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210063535/http://politicalscience.nd.edu/faculty/faculty-list/alan-dowty/|archive-date=10 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>   He was formerly on the faculty of the Hebrew University (Jerusalem), 1964\u20131975, Kahanoff Chair Professor of Israel Studies at the [[University of Calgary]], 2003\u20132006, and President of the Association for Israel Studies, 2005\u20132007. In 2017 he was awarded a Lifetime Achievement Award in Israel Studies by the Association for Israel Studies and the Israel Institute.\n\nHis recent work specialises and focuses on Israeli-American relations, Israel and history  of Zionism, Israeli politics and the [[Arab-Israeli conflict]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to Israel / Palestine online by Alan Dowty |url=http://www.polity.co.uk/dowty/ |accessdate=30 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127034409/http://www.polity.co.uk/dowty/ |archivedate=27 January 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Is Israel Democratic? Substance and Semantics in the \"Ethnic Democracy\" Debate|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/login?auth=0&type=summary&url=/journals/israel_studies/v004/4.2dowty.html|publisher=Project muse|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Ira Sharkansky]] of [[The Hebrew University]] calls Dowty's \"The Jewish State: A Century Later,\" \"the most thorough and sensitive assessment of Israel's democracy that I have seen.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Ezra |last=Mendelsohn |title=? |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |year= 1999 |page= 263}}</ref>. Paul Scham, in Middle East Journal, says that Dowty's book \"Israel/Palestine\" \"now receives pride of place at the top of my list of concise, illuminating histories to recommend.  It can be expected that this book will be a leading contender to be the textbook of choice on the conflict.\"\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nDowty earned a B.A. from [[Shimer College]] (1959) and an M.A. and Ph.D. from the [[University of Chicago]] (1960,1963). In 1964-1975 he was on the faculty of the Hebrew University in Jerusalem, during which time he served as Executive Director of the Leonard Davis Institute for International Relations and Chair of the Department of International Relations. He has been based at the University of Notre Dame since 1975. He returned to Shimer College to teach in 1966 and in 2013, and has also held visitorships at Tel Aviv University, the University of Chicago, Northeastern Illinois University, the University of Illinois at Chicago Circle, the Adlai Stevenson Institute of International Affairs, the Twentieth Century Fund, the University of Haifa, National Defense University, the Oxford Centre for Hebrew and Jewish Studies, Brandeis University, State University of New York at Buffalo, and Catholic University of America.   .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alumni.shimer.edu/s/1028/index.aspx?gid=1&pgid=295|title=Alumni Association Board of Directors|work=Shimer.edu|accessdate=2010-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609203614/http://alumni.shimer.edu/s/1028/index.aspx?pgid=295&gid=1|archive-date=2010-06-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Major Publications==\n*''The Limits of American Isolation'', ([[New York University Press]], 1971)\n*''Middle East Crisis: U.S. Decision Making in 1958, 1970, and 1973'', ([[University of California Press]], 1984)\n*''Closed  Borders: The Contemporary Assault on Freedom of Movement'', ([[Yale University Press]], 1987)\n*''The Jewish State: A Century Later'', ([[University of California Press]], 1998, 2001)\n*''Israel/Palestine'', ([[Polity Press]], 2005, 2008, 2012, 2017)\n*''The Arab-Israel Conflict, Oxford Bibliographies in Political Science (Oxford University Press, 2013, 2015, 2019).\n*''Editor, The Israel/Palestine Reader, (Polity Press), 2019\n*''Arabs and Jews in the Ottoman Empire: Two Worlds Collide (Indiana University Press), 2019\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.amazon.com/Alan-Dowty/e/B001HOKOQ8 Books by Alan Dowty]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dowty, Alan}}\n[[Category:University of Calgary faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Shimer College alumni]]\n[[Category:Shimer College faculty]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n\n\n{{polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| image         = Alan Dowty Shimer College Chicago 2008.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Alan Dowty in 2008.\n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1940|01|15}}\n| occupation    = Professor emeritus\n| education     = BA, MA, Ph.D.\n| alma_mater    = [[Shimer College]]; [[University of Chicago]]\n| genre         = nonfiction\n| subject       = international relations\n}}\n\n'''Alan Dowty''' (born January 15, 1940) is an American author, historian and Professor of International Relations and Political Science Emeritus, [[University of Notre Dame]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Alan Dowty|url=http://politicalscience.nd.edu/faculty/faculty-list/alan-dowty/|publisher=nd.edu|accessdate=30 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210063535/http://politicalscience.nd.edu/faculty/faculty-list/alan-dowty/|archive-date=10 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>   He was formerly on the faculty of the Hebrew University (Jerusalem), 1964-1975, Kahanoff Chair Professor of Israel Studies at the [[University of Calgary]], 2003-2006, and President of the Association for Israel Studies, 2005-2007. In 2017 he was awarded a Lifetime Achievement Award in Israel Studies by the Association for Israel Studies and the Israel Institute.\n\nHis recent work specialises and focuses on Israeli-American relations, Israel and history  of Zionism , Israeli politics and the [[Arab-Israeli conflict]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to Israel / Palestine online by Alan Dowty |url=http://www.polity.co.uk/dowty/ |accessdate=30 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127034409/http://www.polity.co.uk/dowty/ |archivedate=27 January 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Is Israel Democratic? Substance and Semantics in the \"Ethnic Democracy\" Debate|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/login?auth=0&type=summary&url=/journals/israel_studies/v004/4.2dowty.html|publisher=Project muse|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Ira Sharkansky]] of [[The Hebrew University]] calls Dowty's \"The Jewish State: A Century Later,\" \"the most thorough and sensitive assessment of Israel's democracy that I have seen.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Ezra |last=Mendelsohn |title=? |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |year= 1999 |page= 263}}</ref>. Paul Scham, in Middle East Journal, says that Dowty's book \"Israel/Palestine\" \"now receives pride of place at the top of my list of concise, illuminating histories to recommend.  It can be expected that this book will be a leading contender to be the textbook of choice on the conflict.\"\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nDowty earned a B.A. from [[Shimer College]] (1959) and an M.A. and Ph.D. from the [[University of Chicago]] (1960,1963). In 1964-1975 he was on the faculty of the Hebrew University in Jerusalem, during which time he served as Executive Director of the Leonard Davis Institute for International Relations and Chair of the Department of International Relations. He has been based at the University of Notre Dame since 1975. He returned to Shimer College to teach in 1966 and in 2013, and has also held visitorships at Tel Aviv University, the University of Chicago, Northeastern Illinois University, the University of Illinois at Chicago Circle, the Adlai Stevenson Institute of International Affairs, the Twentieth Century Fund, the University of Haifa, National Defense University, the Oxford Centre for Hebrew and Jewish Studies, Brandeis University, State University of New York at Buffalo, and Catholic University of America.   .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alumni.shimer.edu/s/1028/index.aspx?gid=1&pgid=295|title=Alumni Association Board of Directors|work=Shimer.edu|accessdate=2010-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609203614/http://alumni.shimer.edu/s/1028/index.aspx?pgid=295&gid=1|archive-date=2010-06-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Major Publications==\n*''The Limits of American Isolation'', ([[New York University Press]], 1971)\n*''Middle East Crisis: U.S. Decision Making in 1958, 1970, and 1973'', ([[University of California Press]], 1984)\n*''Closed  Borders: The Contemporary Assault on Freedom of Movement'', ([[Yale University Press]], 1987)\n*''The Jewish State: A Century Later'', ([[University of California Press]], 1998, 2001)\n*''Israel/Palestine'', ([[Polity Press]], 2005, 2008, 2012, 2017)\n*''The Arab-Israel Conflict, Oxford Bibliographies in Political Science (Oxford University Press, 2013, 2015, 2019).\n*''Editor, The Israel/Palestine Reader, (Polity Press), 2019\n*''Arabs and Jews in the Ottoman Empire: Two Worlds Collide (Indiana University Press), 2019\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.amazon.com/Alan-Dowty/e/B001HOKOQ8 Books by Alan Dowty]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dowty, Alan}}\n[[Category:University of Calgary faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Shimer College alumni]]\n[[Category:Shimer College faculty]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n\n\n{{polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: ,  \u2192 , , 1964-1975 \u2192 1964\u20131975 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Dowty"}
{"title_page": "Neil Carter (political scientist)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n'''Professor Neil Carter''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[political science|political scientist]] based at the [[University of York]]. \n\nCarter graduated in Politics from [[Durham University]] and completed his postgraduate studies at the [[University of Bath]].<ref name=\"neilcarter\">{{cite web |title=Carter, Neil - Politics |url=https://www.york.ac.uk/politics/staff/academicstaff/neil-carter/#profile-content |website=University of York |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nHis main research and teaching interests have focused on [[environmental politics]] and policy, and on British party politics.<ref name=neilcarter /> His most popular book is ''The Politics of the Environment''. This was originally published in 2001 by [[Cambridge University Press]], with a third, revised edition, released in 2018. He is associate editor of the journal ''[[Environmental Politics (journal)|Environmental Politics]]'', published by Routledge.<ref>{{cite web |title=CARTER Neil |url=http://www.worldwhoswho.com/public/views/entry.html?id=sl2174509 |website=World Who's Who |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nHis publications include<ref>{{cite web |title=Prof. Neil Carter Publications |url=https://pure.york.ac.uk/portal/en/researchers/neil-thomas-carter(4e507651-f4e8-4117-847d-15f665731322)/publications.html |website=University of York |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n* (2004) 'Politics As If Nature Mattered' in A. Leftwich (ed.) What is Politics? (Cambridge: Polity).\n* (2002) 'Environmental Challenges' in P. Heywood, E. Jones and M. Rhodes (eds.) Developments in West European Politics 2, (Basingstoke: Palgrave), pp.&nbsp;221\u2013240.\n* (2002) (with Keith Alderman) 'The Conservative Party Leadership Election of 2001', Parliamentary Affairs 55, 3, 569\u2013585.\n* (2001) The Politics of the Environment (Cambridge University Press). \n* (2001) 'One Step Forward? Greens and the Environment in the 2001 British General Election', Environmental Politics, 10, 4, pp.&nbsp;103\u2013108.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carter, Neil}}\n[[Category:British political scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of York]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bath]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Hatfield College, Durham]]\n\n{{Polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n'''Professor Neil Carter''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[political science|political scientist]] based at the [[University of York]]. \n\nCarter graduated in Politics from [[Durham University]] and completed his postgraduate studies at the [[University of Bath]].<ref name=\"neilcarter\">{{cite web |title=Carter, Neil - Politics |url=https://www.york.ac.uk/politics/staff/academicstaff/neil-carter/#profile-content |website=University of York |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nHis main research and teaching interests have focused on [[environmental politics]] and policy, and on British party politics.<ref name=neilcarter /> His most popular book is ''The Politics of the Environment''. This was originally published in 2001 by [[Cambridge University Press]], with a third, revised edition, released in 2018. He is associate editor of the journal ''[[Environmental Politics (journal)|Environmental Politics]]'', published by Routledge.<ref>{{cite web |title=CARTER Neil |url=http://www.worldwhoswho.com/public/views/entry.html?id=sl2174509 |website=World Who's Who |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nHis publications include<ref>{{cite web |title=Prof. Neil Carter Publications |url=https://pure.york.ac.uk/portal/en/researchers/neil-thomas-carter(4e507651-f4e8-4117-847d-15f665731322)/publications.html |website=University of York |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n* (2004) 'Politics As If Nature Mattered' in A. Leftwich (ed.) What is Politics? (Cambridge: Polity).\n* (2002) 'Environmental Challenges' in P. Heywood, E. Jones and M. Rhodes (eds.) Developments in West European Politics 2, (Basingstoke: Palgrave), pp.&nbsp;221\u2013240.\n* (2002) (with Keith Alderman) 'The Conservative Party Leadership Election of 2001', Parliamentary Affairs 55, 3, 569-585.\n* (2001) The Politics of the Environment (Cambridge University Press). \n* (2001) 'One Step Forward? Greens and the Environment in the 2001 British General Election', Environmental Politics, 10, 4, pp.&nbsp;103\u2013108.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carter, Neil}}\n[[Category:British political scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of York]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bath]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Hatfield College, Durham]]\n\n{{Polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublications:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 569-585 \u2192 569\u2013585", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neil_Carter_(political_scientist)"}
{"title_page": "Yevgeny Adamov", "text_new": "[[File:EvgenyAdamov.jpg|thumb|Yevgeny Adamov with [[President of Russia]] [[Vladimir Putin]] in [[Chelyabinsk Oblast]] on 31 March 2000.]]\n'''Yevgeny Olegovich Adamov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u041e\u043b\u0435\u0301\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0410\u0434\u0430\u0301\u043c\u043e\u0432}}, born April 28, 1939) was the head of the [[Russia]]n [[Nuclear power|atomic energy]] ministry, [[MinAtom]].  He was appointed by President [[Boris Yeltsin]] in 1998 and ousted by President [[Vladimir Putin]] in 2001.\n\nAdamov, a nuclear physicist, then joined the [[Dollezhal Institute]]. From 1986 until 1998, Adamov directed NIKIET, a Russian government nuclear research and design institute. <ref>{{cite web| title = StAR Databases: Corruption Cases: Yevgeny Adamov| url =http://star.worldbank.org/corruption-cases/node/18672| accessdate = March 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, he was arrested in [[Bern]], [[Switzerland]], on [[fraud]] charges. the arrest was made at the request of the [[United States]].  The US accused Adamov of diverting up to US$9 million which the US Energy Department gave Russia to help improve security at its nuclear facilities.  [[Extradition]] requests were filed first by the US and then by Russia, which has protested about the move by the US. Adamov was finally extradited to Russia. The move was widely covered as a successful ploy by the Russian government to prevent Adamov from telling US authorities state secrets that he knew. <ref>[http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/Home/Archive/Russia_demands_extradition_of_arrested_minister.html?cid=4514542 Russia demands extradition of arrested minister], swissinfo, 19 May 2005.</ref> \n\nIn 2008, Adamov was convicted in Russia of abuse of office and defrauding the Russian government of some $31 million in United States aid funds intended for security upgrades for aging [[nuclear reactors]]. \n\nOn February 20, 2008, he was convicted by the Zamoskvoretsky court in Moscow, Russia of fraud and misuse of power and sentenced to 5.5 years of imprisonment.<ref>[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc.aspx?DocsID=855218 Yevgeni Adamov Sentenced to 5.5 Years of Prison], [[Kommersant]], February 20, 2008.</ref>\n\nHe was released from jail when his sentence was suspended by a higher-level court on April 17, 2008.<ref>[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc.aspx?docsid=883807 Yevgeni Adamov's conviction is now  suspended], [[Kommersant]], April 18, 2008.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.novayagazeta.ru/rassled2/minatom/karta.shtml Investigation by Novaya Gazeta (Russian)]\n\n{{polisci-bio-stub}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adamov, Yevgeny}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Moscow Aviation Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Russian physicists]]\n[[Category:Russian nuclear physicists]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Russian fraudsters]]\n[[Category:People extradited from Switzerland]]\n[[Category:People extradited to Russia]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:EvgenyAdamov.jpg|thumb|Yevgeny Adamov with [[President of Russia]] [[Vladimir Putin]] in [[Chelyabinsk Oblast]] on 31 March 2000.]]\n'''Yevgeny Olegovich Adamov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u041e\u043b\u0435\u0301\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0410\u0434\u0430\u0301\u043c\u043e\u0432}}, born April 28, 1939) was the head of the [[Russia]]n [[Nuclear power|atomic energy]] ministry, [[MinAtom]].  He was appointed by President [[Boris Yeltsin]] in 1998 and ousted by President [[Vladimir Putin]] in 2001.\n\nAdamov, a nuclear physicist, then joined the [[Dollezhal Institute]]. From 1986 until 1998, Adamov directed NIKIET, a Russian government nuclear research and design institute. <ref>{{cite web| title = StAR Databases: Corruption Cases: Yevgeny Adamov| url =http://star.worldbank.org/corruption-cases/node/18672| accessdate = March 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, he was arrested in [[Bern]], [[Switzerland]], on [[fraud]] charges. the arrest was made at the request of the [[United States]].  The US accused Adamov of diverting up to US$9 million which the US Energy Department gave Russia to help improve security at its nuclear facilities.  [[Extradition]] requests were filed first by the USA and then by Russia, which has protested about the move by the US. Adamov was finally extradited to Russia. The move was widely covered as a successful ploy by the Russian government to prevent Adamov from telling US authorities state secrets that he knew. <ref>[http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/Home/Archive/Russia_demands_extradition_of_arrested_minister.html?cid=4514542 Russia demands extradition of arrested minister], swissinfo, 19 May 2005.</ref> \n\nIn 2008, Adamov was convicted in Russia of abuse of office and defrauding the Russian government of some $31 million in United States aid funds intended for security upgrades for aging [[nuclear reactors]]. \n\nOn February 20, 2008, he was convicted by the Zamoskvoretsky court in Moscow, Russia of fraud and misuse of power and sentenced to 5.5 years of imprisonment.<ref>[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc.aspx?DocsID=855218 Yevgeni Adamov Sentenced to 5.5 Years of Prison], [[Kommersant]], February 20, 2008.</ref>\n\nHe was released from jail when his sentence was suspended by a higher-level court on April 17, 2008.<ref>[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc.aspx?docsid=883807 Yevgeni Adamov's conviction is now  suspended], [[Kommersant]], April 18, 2008.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.novayagazeta.ru/rassled2/minatom/karta.shtml Investigation by Novaya Gazeta (Russian)]\n\n{{polisci-bio-stub}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adamov, Yevgeny}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Moscow Aviation Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Russian physicists]]\n[[Category:Russian nuclear physicists]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Russian fraudsters]]\n[[Category:People extradited from Switzerland]]\n[[Category:People extradited to Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: the USA \u2192 the US", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yevgeny_Adamov"}
{"title_page": "Curfews and lockdowns related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of restrictions imposed due to COVID-19}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:CRPF trooper during Curfew.png|thumb|Officer of the [[Central Armed Police Forces]] during national COVID-19 curfew in India.]]\n[[File:High Street and Curfew Tower, Cushendall, Co. Antrim - geograph.org.uk - 1381257.jpg|thumb|Empty street in Cushendall, [[Northern Ireland]], UK]]\n[[File:6954Baliuag enhanced community quarantine 37.jpg|thumb|2020 [[Curfew Pass]] in Baliuag, Phillippines.]]\n[[File:Mahane Yehuda Market closed in coronavirus outbreak.jpg|thumb|Mahane Yehuda Market in Jerusalem.]]\nThis list of '''COVID-19 related curfews and lockdowns''' shows [[curfew]]s and similar restrictions (known as [[stay-at-home order]], shelter-in-place order, [[Shutdown (economics)|shutdown]]/[[lockdown]]) to prevent further infection with [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2), which causes [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19),  worldwide ([[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]). Lockdowns across nations and regions may be of varying stringency.\n\n==List==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country !! Main article !! Type of regulation !! Start date !! Expiry date !! References\n|-\n|{{ALB}} || || curfew from 13:00 to 05:00 on Mondays to Saturdays<br>total lockdown on Sundays || March 13 || || <ref>{{cite web |title=Albanians begin life under daily curfew as coronavirus cases rise |url=https://de.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-albania-curfew/albanians-begin-life-under-daily-curfew-as-coronavirus-cases-rise-idINL8N2BG91I |website=Reuters |language=de |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{DZA}} || || curfew in the capital city from 19:00 to 07:00<br>full lockdown in town of Blida || || || <ref>{{cite web |title=Algeria imposes curfew in capital |url=https://fr.reuters.com/article/healthcareSector/idUSL8N2BG8QU |web